  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Friday</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I am longing to go down to Ockham; &amp; believe that I shall certainly not delay it beyond Sunday. I want to get to my Harp &amp; my Horses, &amp; the dear little Birds.</p>
      <p>As a matter of reason &amp; principle more than of mania, I have made up my mind to make the</p>
      <p>utmost for one year of my Harp; but by no means in an excessive way, or to the exclusion of other things. But I intend to make that the chief; on purpose. Just for that limited time, &amp; avoiding mania. What I wish is to devote a steady unvarying attention to it, just for a period. Not 6 hours one day, 1 the next, &amp; none the 3d; &amp; so forth. I am sure you</p>
      <p>will approve all this.</p>
      <p>And I believe that this week in Town has done much toward inclining me to the country still more, &amp; to a steady interest and application to rational &amp; elegant pursuits.--</p>
      <p>The enclosed must be about L. King surely. It is from the Chronicle But I did not see it. Charlotte sent it to me.</p>
      <p>Are you not also delighted with the enclosed little Horse. I saw much</p>
      <p>more about it in yesterday's paper (which you will get tomorrow). The dear little thing was put into a Cab, like a Dog; &amp; carried about also in its master's arms.</p>
    </div></body>
